The problem being solved: I needed a robust, automated way to validate the functionality, performance, and cross-browser compatibility of my interactive online CV. Beyond simply testing the site, I wanted to establish a comparative baseline for the industry's leading automation tools to evaluate their relative execution speeds, developer experience, and reporting capabilities against a single, consistent target application.

Key design decisions: I architected a unified repository containing three distinct test suites targeting the same application, utilizing Playwright, Cypress, and Robot Framework.

Playwright was implemented for its native parallelization and deep cross-browser context isolation.

Cypress was utilized to demonstrate proficiency in its developer-centric, time-travel debugging environment.

Robot Framework was integrated to showcase keyword-driven testing, separating the technical implementation from high-level, business-readable test cases.

Any trade-offs considered: The primary trade-off was the deliberate acceptance of code duplication and increased maintenance overhead. Writing the same test scenarios across three different frameworks violates the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle in a traditional production environment. However, I traded this architectural purity for the opportunity to build a comprehensive portfolio piece that acts as a live comparative analysis of these tools.

Why you selected this example: This repository serves as a direct, executable proof of my versatility as a Senior SDET. It demonstrates that I am not just tied to a single tool syntax, but rather that I understand the underlying mechanics of modern UI automation and can architect solutions across various testing paradigms, from keyword-driven Python/Robot environments to modern JavaScript/TypeScript ecosystems.

